            android:layout_marginTop="424dp"
            android:text="Since the COVID-19 outbreak, nations have faced significant challenges with the generation, collection, treatment, and disposal of waste.  One of the direct consequences of the pandemic has been a 40 percent increase in the global production of biomedical waste.  Although comprehensive data is yet to be published, biomedical waste appears to be increasing in India.  For instance, a June 2020 Hindustan Times article reported that daily biomedical waste generated by medical institutions in Delhi have increased from 500 grams per bed to an average of 2.5 kg to 4 kg per bed in recent months. In an annual report, the Central Pollution Control Board (CPCB) estimated that India had generated 3,360,043 tons of plastic between 2018 and 2019. However, COVID-19 has led to several countries, including India, to relax their regulations on plastic. For instance, despite pre-pandemic efforts to phase out single-use plastics in India by 2022, several states such as Kerala and Delhi have relaxed statewide bans on plastics."
            android:textAlignment="center"
            android:textSize="12sp"
            app:layout_constraintEnd_toEndOf="parent"
            app:layout_constraintHorizontal_bias="0.0"
            app:layout_constraintStart_toStartOf="parent"
